in films from Hollywood to Hong Kong, from top-grossing to direct-to-video, and from cop-action movies to X-rated skin flicks. Contributors from a variety of disciplines analyze violent women's respective places in the history of cinema, in the lives of viewers, and in the feminist response to male violence against women. The essays in part one, "Genre Films," turn to film cycles in which violent women have routinely appeared. The essays in part two, "New Bonds and New Communities," analyze movies singly or in pairs to determine how women's movie brutality fosters solidarity amongst the characters or their audiences. All of the contributions look at films not simply in terms of whether they properly represent women or feminist principles, but also as texts with social contexts and possible uses in the re-construction of masculinity and femininity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aViolence in motion pictures. 0aWomen in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh1 aArons, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Jeffrey A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDole, Carol M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrindstaff, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalberstam, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Neal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Neal, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKnobloch, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCaughey, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCaughey, Martha, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMiller, Barbara L., 